Elon Musk has announced a delay in Cybertruck deliveries in California as Tesla donates several vehicles to assist communities affected by the Palisades and Eaton fires. The Altadena Mountain Rescue Team shared a photo on social media of donated Cybertrucks, which will provide power and free Wi-Fi to areas without electricity, including the sheriff's station.

According to Tesla's website, Cybertrucks can serve as backup power sources for homes for up to three days. The donated trucks are also equipped with Starlink terminals to deliver free internet access. Musk stated that more Cybertrucks will be deployed to affected areas across Los Angeles and Malibu to act as mobile base stations.

In a post on X, Musk apologized to customers awaiting deliveries, explaining the urgent need for these vehicles in disaster relief efforts:
"Apologies to those expecting Cybertruck deliveries in California over the next few days. We need to use those trucks as mobile base stations to provide power to Starlink Internet terminals in areas of LA without connectivity. A new truck will be delivered end of week," Musk wrote.

Currently, about 150,000 people in Los Angeles County remain under evacuation orders due to the fires, with more than 700 residents seeking refuge in nine shelters, according to local authorities. Los Angeles County Sheriff Robert Luna said that evacuation orders for the Palisades area are unlikely to be lifted until red flag warnings expire on Wednesday evening.
This move underscores Tesla's growing emphasis on leveraging its technologies for disaster relief, combining Cybertruck capabilities with Starlink internet to provide essential services to communities in crisis.

